together for 12 years, the four of us, and
I feel very lucky that we've had

00:28:22.480 --> 00:28:28.240
that and we can help our second graders
grow.

00:28:25.640 --> 00:28:31.359
After 30 years, I can still say that I
love my job

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:35.159
even though at times it feels impossible.

00:28:33.119 --> 00:28:39.400
Um, after school on Tuesday, I sat down at
my desk, which by the way is a tool

00:28:37.200 --> 00:28:42.360
in an elementary school classroom. We

00:28:39.400 --> 00:28:44.759
actually never sit at our desks except

00:28:42.359 --> 00:28:46.839
for maybe after school, and there was

00:28:44.759 --> 00:28:51.359
this little note on my desk, and it had a

00:28:46.839 --> 00:28:53.559
big heart. I opened up the letter

00:28:51.359 --> 00:28:57.440
and it said, "Dear Ms. Brandl, I like how
you always make me feel good." And I

00:28:55.920 --> 00:29:01.480
said, "That's why I've been doing this for
30

00:28:58.839 --> 00:29:04.119
years. If I can just help kids feel good

00:29:01.480 --> 00:29:06.680
and grow and become wonderful people,

00:29:04.119 --> 00:29:09.200
then I've done my job." Thank you so much.

00:29:11.720 --> 00:29:15.880
Thank you, Nicole. I'm [clears throat] a
little

00:29:13.920 --> 00:29:18.120
disappointed that I do not see a drum

00:29:15.880 --> 00:29:22.680
set for the next speaker, but I guess he
forgot to bring it. Carolyn Castellano.

00:29:25.039 --> 00:29:30.360
Hey, thank you so much. Thank you,
Brookline. Um

00:29:28.200 --> 00:29:35.079
Bob, I remember sitting in your office
when I got hired, and we talked about

00:29:32.480 --> 00:29:36.079
Rage Against the Machine.

00:29:35.079 --> 00:29:40.000
I don't know if you remember that. The
microphone explodes, breaking the

00:29:38.079 --> 00:29:43.720
pattern. I think you were rapping it, not
me.

00:29:43.920 --> 00:29:50.119
Anyway, it's been great. Um I'm not going
to talk too long because I talked um

00:29:48.160 --> 00:29:53.879
recently here about my journey at
Brookline, which has been an amazing

00:29:51.839 --> 00:29:58.160
time here. I think I just want to think
about the connections we make

00:29:56.359 --> 00:30:02.640
with students and especially being here
for so long. I remember my very first

00:30:00.279 --> 00:30:06.119
student, Samdorf, whom I'm still in touch

00:30:02.640 --> 00:30:08.920
with today. Um or just recently, another

00:30:06.119 --> 00:30:12.519
student, um I was asked to go to one of
the um Celtics playoff

00:30:11.440 --> 00:30:17.279
games. A friend of mine was playing
trumpet at it and um I I couldn't go

00:30:15.440 --> 00:30:20.240
last minute, and he said, "Well, do you
know someone else who wants to go to the

00:30:18.720 --> 00:30:23.759
game?" I thought of a student.

00:30:22.240 --> 00:30:26.799
I contacted him and asked, "Do you want to
go to the Celtics game tonight?"

00:30:25.160 --> 00:30:30.720
He said, "Yes." They went to the game.

00:30:28.759 --> 00:30:34.319
They watched warm-ups and met some
players.

00:30:32.400 --> 00:30:38.159
Not Reggie Lewis. I think it was someone
else. Anyway,

00:30:36.599 --> 00:30:40.480
those connections are what I will always
remember.

00:30:39.119 --> 00:30:44.079
I connect with the students.

00:30:42.079 --> 00:30:47.599
It feels good to know I made a difference.

00:30:45.079 --> 00:30:51.119
They see me, and I see them, like a
mirror.

00:30:47.599 --> 00:30:53.679
We keep that connection even when they
leave.

00:30:51.119 --> 00:30:58.000
It's awesome.

00:30:56.480 --> 00:31:01.480
The best part of my job is the connections
with the students.

00:31:00.319 --> 00:31:05.440
That's all I want to say. Thank you.

00:31:03.200 --> 00:31:08.240
I’m sorry, I don’t have drums. I will
bring them next time.

00:31:05.440 --> 00:31:11.920
Thank you, Carolyn. Next is Deborah
Caruso.

00:31:09.400 --> 00:31:13.440
Props are great.

00:31:11.920 --> 00:31:16.759
Hello. Thank you, everyone. Thank you,
School Committee (the elected board that runs the public schools) for this honor.

00:31:23.400 --> 00:31:26.160
I am one of the 31s.

00:31:28.279 --> 00:31:34.679
I started here in 1995 and know many faces
in this room.

00:31:31.599 --> 00:31:37.559
I am not a teacher. I am an occupational
therapist.

00:31:34.680 --> 00:31:39.759
I help those quiet voices that don't
always get heard. I promised not to cry.

00:31:37.559 --> 00:31:42.159
I have a parent on the School Committee
whose son graduated this year with my child.

00:31:39.759 --> 00:31:44.799
I feel like my two boys graduated
together.

00:31:42.160 --> 00:31:47.360
All the kids I work with are my kids.

00:31:44.799 --> 00:31:51.479
I was asked to share a special moment.

00:31:49.279 --> 00:31:55.480
I brought my first Brookline Special
Education Parent Advisory Council (SEPAC) Hero Award.

00:31:53.759 --> 00:32:00.079
I earned it in 2019, and it was the
highlight of my career.

00:31:57.960 --> 00:32:04.960
Since I started, I got my master's in
autism care and my doctorate in autism and trauma-informed practice.

00:32:03.160 --> 00:32:08.759
But nothing can top this award because it
came from the parents.

00:32:05.920 --> 00:32:12.720
My job is to advocate for those who need
help.

00:32:08.759 --> 00:32:15.879
brought in my very first Brookline SEPAC

00:32:12.720 --> 00:32:18.120
Hero Award which I earned in 2019 and

00:32:15.880 --> 00:32:20.600
this was the highlight of my career.

00:32:18.119 --> 00:32:23.199
Um I've uh since I started here, I got

00:32:20.599 --> 00:32:25.639
my master's in autism care, I got my

00:32:23.200 --> 00:32:27.680
doctor's degree in autism and

00:32:25.640 --> 00:32:31.040
trauma-informed practice, but nothing

00:32:27.680 --> 00:32:32.759
can top this award because this came

00:32:31.039 --> 00:32:35.960
from the parents. And at the end of the

00:32:32.759 --> 00:32:38.519
day, my job is to advocate for those who

00:32:35.960 --> 00:32:41.279
Some kids can't always speak up for
themselves.

00:32:38.519 --> 00:32:44.400
Those kids are sometimes called not always
our kids,

00:32:41.279 --> 00:32:46.000
but your kids.

00:32:44.400 --> 00:32:49.000
At the end of the day, this is why I am
here.

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:51.839
Everyone asks me after my master's degree,
"Will you keep working?"

00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:54.599
Yes, I will keep working.

00:32:53.119 --> 00:32:57.599
After my doctorate, "Will you keep
working?"

00:32:56.319 --> 00:33:00.319
Yes, I will keep working.

00:32:58.759 --> 00:33:05.039
"Don't you want to be a manager?"

00:33:02.799 --> 00:33:09.519
No, I don't want to be a manager.

00:33:07.319 --> 00:33:12.159
The kids are my reason for being here.

00:33:09.519 --> 00:33:14.680
I have been working for 31 years,

00:33:12.160 --> 00:33:18.519
but I feel like I have 15 more years to
give.

00:33:16.559 --> 00:33:22.960
When I walk through the playground

00:33:21.240 --> 00:33:27.799
and hear 40 or 50 children call me Dr.
Caruso and come to hug me,

00:33:24.759 --> 00:33:30.440
that is why I am here.

00:33:27.799 --> 00:33:32.759
Thank you for letting me help raise so
many of your children,

00:33:30.440 --> 00:33:36.120
to help them feel like they belong,

00:33:32.759 --> 00:33:38.240
to help them feel part of our community,

00:33:36.119 --> 00:33:41.440
no matter what the outside world says.

00:33:40.039 --> 00:33:46.240
All my kids on Individualized Education
Plans (IEPs)

00:33:44.880 --> 00:33:50.279
and all my kids with special needs are my
kids.

00:33:48.039 --> 00:33:52.559
They are all our kids.

00:33:50.279 --> 00:33:55.759
Thank you for letting me share this with
you.

00:33:54.000 --> 00:34:00.400
I will say my son just graduated,

00:33:57.960 --> 00:34:03.240
along with Donna's son.

00:34:01.920 --> 00:34:06.897
I won’t say any names, I promise.

00:34:05.640 --> 00:34:08.918
But I also wanted my son to be in the
public schools of Brookline.

00:34:11.760 --> 00:34:15.560
So, we are a Brookline family.

00:34:18.032 --> 00:34:20.052
I have spent my whole adult life working
for this community,

00:34:26.679 --> 00:34:32.119
and my son is now part of this community.

00:34:30.599 --> 00:34:36.719
Thank you for the privilege of being a
part of all of you.

00:34:35.039 --> 00:34:41.519
Yeah. [applause]

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:45.599
Thank you, Deborah.

00:34:43.519 --> 00:34:48.639
Elizabeth Gorman.

00:34:46.960 --> 00:34:53.120
[applause]

00:34:50.719 --> 00:34:55.878
Liz Gorman.

00:34:53.119 --> 00:34:58.480
All right.

00:34:55.878 --> 00:35:00.920
I have the microphone.

00:34:58.480 --> 00:35:05.119
Thank you to my family,

00:35:02.960 --> 00:35:08.523
One surprise is that it has not gotten
easier.

00:35:06.503 --> 00:35:08.523
[laughter]

00:35:08.559 --> 00:35:13.920
I have more skills, but I still work

00:35:11.679 --> 00:35:16.239
long hours. I never feel caught up. My

00:35:13.920 --> 00:35:18.880
husband can confirm.

00:35:16.239 --> 00:35:22.199
Sadly, I still feel dread

00:35:18.880 --> 00:35:25.760
on Sunday nights and after vacations.

00:35:22.199 --> 00:35:27.519
We are on every day, all day.

00:35:25.760 --> 00:35:30.120
I wish for a job that I don't

00:35:27.519 --> 00:35:33.639
bring home every day and every weekend.

00:35:30.119 --> 00:35:35.719
But the stress goes away every

00:35:33.639 --> 00:35:40.319
Monday morning when I am in my classroom
with students.

00:35:38.079 --> 00:35:44.720
It's a happy place for me and seems to be
for many of you.

00:35:42.320 --> 00:35:47.680
Another surprise is that it is just

00:35:44.719 --> 00:35:51.000
as fun and exciting as it was 30

00:35:47.679 --> 00:35:52.399
years ago. That is a good surprise.

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:56.519
I am not a teacher known for a single
great

00:35:54.639 --> 00:36:01.039
achievement, but I am proud of a few
things I helped create.

00:35:58.519 --> 00:36:04.840
I helped create a China exchange, the
climbing wall,

00:36:03.119 --> 00:36:07.480
a network of mindfulness work with

00:36:04.840 --> 00:36:10.920
teachers, and many Spanish curriculum

00:36:07.480 --> 00:36:13.970
units. My teaching, like most teachers,
which to clarify is not

00:36:13.400 --> 00:36:17.879
over, [laughter]

00:36:14.800 --> 00:36:20.480
has been defined by a lot of effort

00:36:17.880 --> 00:36:24.840
and made of many small moments of joy and
kindness.

00:36:22.519 --> 00:36:26.519
It is not a thankless job.

00:36:24.840 --> 00:36:31.119
In addition to the daily delights, every
year around this time

00:36:29.119 --> 00:36:35.585
the thank you cards come in. I keep a
folder

00:36:33.079 --> 00:36:38.559
labeled nice. [laughter]

00:36:36.679 --> 00:36:43.239
The special ones are making it nice and
full. This note

00:36:41.519 --> 00:36:48.039
that I will share is from a student. This
note

00:36:45.840 --> 00:36:52.039
came unexpectedly in October of this year
and

00:36:51.280 --> 00:36:55.880
shows what I am most proud of.

00:36:54.559 --> 00:37:00.039
I will change the name for privacy. The
email said,

00:36:58.199 --> 00:37:02.480
"Hi Ms.

00:37:00.039 --> 00:37:06.599
Gorman. I'm Emma and I had you for my
junior year Spanish class about 4 years

00:37:04.440 --> 00:37:08.599
ago. I just wanted to reach out and say

00:37:06.599 --> 00:37:11.839
thank you. During my junior year of high

00:37:08.599 --> 00:37:14.360
school, I struggled with my mental health

00:37:11.840 --> 00:37:16.760
and you honestly saved my life.

00:37:14.360 --> 00:37:21.360
You asked me to stay after class one day
and wanted to know why I was missing so many classes.

00:37:18.760 --> 00:37:25.760
It didn’t feel like a confrontation. It
felt like you cared.

00:37:23.039 --> 00:37:28.920
We started to talk regularly.

00:37:25.760 --> 00:37:30.720
Having one person care about me then was
what I needed to stay alive.

00:37:28.920 --> 00:37:34.559
Now I am a junior in college in
Philadelphia. I am studying to be an elementary school teacher.

00:37:33.039 --> 00:37:39.119
[laughter] If I become half the teacher
and person you are, I will feel successful.

00:37:37.239 --> 00:37:41.139
Thank you so much for helping me,
especially when I needed it the most.

00:37:39.119 --> 00:37:45.400
I hope this email reaches you and I hope
you have a great school year.

00:37:43.400 --> 00:37:50.039
Best, Emma. Every teacher makes a
difference, and we often don’t know when.

00:37:47.679 --> 00:37:54.199
Please trust the School Committee (the
elected board that runs the public schools).

00:37:52.119 --> 00:37:55.759
Please keep trusting and supporting
teachers to follow their passions.

00:37:54.199 --> 00:38:00.360
Help create good conditions so they can
show up healthy for others.

00:37:57.519 --> 00:38:02.000
Please keep our class sizes small.

00:38:00.360 --> 00:38:05.239
[laughter] This way we can know every
person in our rooms.

00:38:03.639 --> 00:38:09.519
I am so excited that Emma will soon be a
future teacher.

00:38:07.599 --> 00:38:12.799
Thank you and congratulations to you all.

00:38:09.519 --> 00:38:16.200
[applause] Thank you, Liz. Michelle
Greeley.

00:38:15.146 --> 00:38:21.319
[applause] Thank you very much, School
Committee (the elected board that runs the public schools).

00:38:19.039 --> 00:38:24.000
This is such an honor. It is also an honor
but a little scary to realize my gray hairs are coming in faster.

00:38:21.320 --> 00:38:27.960
As a BEEP (the Boston Early Education
Program) teacher, I’ve taught at FRR (the Frederick School),

00:38:29.556 --> 00:38:31.576
the Lynch Center, Driscoll, Lincoln, and
now I teach pre-K at BEEP (the Boston Early Education Program) at Putterham.

00:38:33.800 --> 00:38:37.640
My classroom, no matter where it is, feels
like my home away from home.

00:38:41.346 --> 00:38:48.079
I would like to take you all on a field
trip there right now.

00:38:45.800 --> 00:38:52.360
For this trip, please humor me and close
your eyes when I count to three.

00:38:50.280 --> 00:38:55.160
With your eyes closed, you can imagine all
the sights.

00:38:52.360 --> 00:38:57.920
You will hear four and five-year-olds
describe the map that takes you to PKG.

00:38:55.159 --> 00:39:00.199
1 2 3.

00:38:57.920 --> 00:39:04.159
Now, close your eyes and imagine, for this
is BEEP (the Boston Early Education Program) at Putterham.

00:39:02.760 --> 00:39:09.119
First, you ring the buzzer.

00:39:06.280 --> 00:39:11.160
is my home away from home.

00:39:09.119 --> 00:39:15.079
I'd like to take you all on a field trip
there right now.

00:39:12.599 --> 00:39:19.319
Now, for this trip, I'd like to you to all
humor me and close your eyes once I

00:39:17.880 --> 00:39:24.480
count to three. With your eyes shut,
you'll be able to

00:39:21.239 --> 00:39:27.119
envision all the sights as you listen to

00:39:24.480 --> 00:39:29.800
four and five-year-olds describe the map

00:39:27.119 --> 00:39:32.440
that leads to PKG.

00:39:29.800 --> 00:39:35.160
1 2 3.

00:39:32.440 --> 00:39:38.440
Now, close your eyes and imagine, for

00:39:35.159 --> 00:39:40.599
this is BEEP at Putterham.

00:39:38.440 --> 00:39:43.599
First, you ring the buzzer.

00:39:40.599 --> 00:39:45.000
Then, you push one of the two doors. On

00:39:43.599 --> 00:39:50.319
the other side is the door to the
playground. There are many windows there.

00:39:48.559 --> 00:39:53.000
The stairs are in the middle.

00:39:50.320 --> 00:39:56.159
Follow the arrows up the stairs. We are
going straight to near where the

00:39:54.559 --> 00:39:59.599
elevator is. Do not use that elevator if
there is a

00:39:58.360 --> 00:40:03.799
fire. This is the glass door to go inside.

00:40:02.440 --> 00:40:08.480
Now, I want to thank my dad for that fire
safety tip because he worked for

00:40:06.480 --> 00:40:13.400
many years as a firefighter in Newton and
shared great fire safety tips with

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:16.360
all of my students.

00:40:14.679 --> 00:40:21.320
Now, here you are. This is a picture of
all the friends at school. There are

00:40:18.639 --> 00:40:23.879
all the teachers. All up on the side is

00:40:21.320 --> 00:40:26.320
a long hallway. The letters right

00:40:23.880 --> 00:40:29.760
here means it's the classroom.

00:40:26.320 --> 00:40:31.039
Abracadabra, everyone open your eyes.

00:40:29.760 --> 00:40:36.519
We are here. You have just arrived in a
corner of a

00:40:32.840 --> 00:40:38.800
BEEP classroom where true learning
happens.

00:40:36.519 --> 00:40:42.920
The magic happens as the students here
learn from each other.

00:40:40.760 --> 00:40:46.840
The joy happens as they celebrate and
praise each other.

00:40:44.760 --> 00:40:50.280
Now, I would like you to listen to their

00:40:46.840 --> 00:40:53.079
joy. These are their words.

00:40:50.280 --> 00:40:55.240
I love your book so much and it's funny.

00:40:53.079 --> 00:40:58.840
And thank you very much for making it.

00:40:55.239 --> 00:41:00.879
It's so cute and I love it so much. I

00:40:58.840 --> 00:41:03.559
love your story.

00:41:00.880 --> 00:41:06.360
It is like a wow maze. I love your

00:41:03.559 --> 00:41:10.360
pictures that you made. I love that you
can read. I love the letters that you

00:41:09.119 --> 00:41:15.680
can form. I really like your drawing. I
love how

00:41:13.559 --> 00:41:18.559
well you are reading. You are just doing

00:41:15.679 --> 00:41:21.000
so great.

00:41:18.559 --> 00:41:23.920
In BEEP, we never underestimate the

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:25.880
power of a word or a gesture.

00:41:23.920 --> 00:41:28.760
The words that we choose help others to

00:41:25.880 --> 00:41:31.160
feel loved, special, appreciated,

00:41:28.760 --> 00:41:33.920
valued, and respected.

00:41:31.159 --> 00:41:36.719
Just as important as our words are

00:41:33.920 --> 00:41:38.760
the gestures of those who cannot

00:41:36.719 --> 00:41:43.640
speak. Positive gestures, handshakes,

00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:46.760
movements, whispers, and eye contact

00:41:43.639 --> 00:41:49.279
carry the same meaning as our words.

00:41:46.760 --> 00:41:52.520
Some of my best times in BEEP were

00:41:49.280 --> 00:41:55.480
dancing with a nonverbal learner.

00:41:52.519 --> 00:41:58.440
Her smiles and laughter were like sweet
treats.

00:41:55.480 --> 00:42:00.000
That is really true.

00:41:58.440 --> 00:42:04.679
I came to Brookline because the schools
care about different people.

00:42:01.719 --> 00:42:07.039
They celebrate our differences.

00:42:04.679 --> 00:42:11.000
I have been all around Brookline.

00:42:09.400 --> 00:42:15.559
I know that Brookline is a place for
everyone.

00:42:13.519 --> 00:42:19.960
It is a place where we all feel valued
together.

00:42:17.920 --> 00:42:24.639
Thank you to everyone in Brookline.

00:42:22.920 --> 00:42:28.759
A special thanks to Margaret, our
principal, Rachel, Aaron, and all the helpers and coworkers I have worked with.

00:42:26.400 --> 00:42:31.760
I also want to thank my dad.

00:42:28.760 --> 00:42:34.320
He taught me to love maps.

00:42:31.760 --> 00:42:36.640
Dad, you have always guided me.

00:42:34.320 --> 00:42:38.960
Thank you for always being there.

00:42:36.639 --> 00:42:43.599
My dad was a firefighter in Newton for 40
years.

00:42:41.280 --> 00:42:47.639
I plan to be here for a longer time.

00:42:45.840 --> 00:42:52.440
To my mom who showed me how to inspire
kids with fun projects.

00:42:50.480 --> 00:42:56.599
As a preschool teacher, she taught me to
be patient and caring.

00:42:54.639 --> 00:43:01.559
Thank you to my daughters, Joella and
Julia.

00:42:59.960 --> 00:43:06.279
They share their mom, me, day and night
with my students and their families.

00:43:04.039 --> 00:43:10.760
They help me in many ways.

00:43:08.519 --> 00:43:13.600
Thank you. Thank you.

00:43:13.829 --> 00:43:15.849
[applause]

00:43:17.920 --> 00:43:22.440
Thank you, Michelle. Lisa Lamont Harris.

00:43:24.963 --> 00:43:26.983
[applause and cheering]

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:38.480
Okay. How do you tell 30 years in 3
minutes?

00:43:36.679 --> 00:43:42.880
I will use a few short points.

00:43:40.840 --> 00:43:47.280
I am a teacher at heart, so there is a
lesson here.

00:43:45.239 --> 00:43:51.320
Here we go.

00:43:48.920 --> 00:43:54.800
Lessons I learned from 30 years in the
public schools of Brookline.

00:43:53.400 --> 00:43:58.920
Lesson number one: Follow your heart.

00:43:57.119 --> 00:44:03.000
Do not be afraid to take a chance on love.

00:44:01.119 --> 00:44:07.320
Give up your secure job as a teacher in
Connecticut.

00:44:05.199 --> 00:44:09.679
Leave what is familiar.

00:44:07.320 --> 00:44:13.120
Leave your family and friends.

00:44:09.679 --> 00:44:16.119
Follow that special person to a new and
exciting city.

00:44:13.119 --> 00:44:18.400
It might just turn out well. Thank you,
Jason. I love you.

00:44:16.119 --> 00:44:21.359
Number two,

00:44:18.400 --> 00:44:24.160
Jason. I love you.

00:44:21.360 --> 00:44:27.120
Um number two,

00:44:24.159 --> 00:44:29.519
When your job interview starts, Bob,
you'll

00:44:27.119 --> 00:44:33.319
know right away, it begins with a

00:44:29.519 --> 00:44:34.599
surprise juggling act by the principal,

00:44:33.320 --> 00:44:40.319
okay? Do not worry.

00:44:36.599 --> 00:44:42.400
Just think about the idea.

00:44:40.320 --> 00:44:45.960
There is a lot to handle as a teacher. We
keep many things

00:44:44.880 --> 00:44:49.960
up in the air, and some days feel like a

00:44:47.960 --> 00:44:53.280
circus.

00:44:49.960 --> 00:44:56.880
And when he offers you the job, you

00:44:53.280 --> 00:44:58.630
say yes. Thank you, Tom Cavanagh.

00:44:56.880 --> 00:45:03.119
I started at Baker, [applause] spent some
time here at Town Hall, and

00:45:00.880 --> 00:45:05.400
I'm happily at Beebe now. Thank

00:45:03.119 --> 00:45:08.480
you, Margaret.

00:45:05.400 --> 00:45:12.840
Number three, learn from others.

00:45:08.480 --> 00:45:12.840
Wise words from Alyssa Henry.

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:19.159
Half of teaching is acting.

00:45:16.800 --> 00:45:22.960
Have fun and put on a show for your
students every day.

00:45:22.119 --> 00:45:27.199
All right. Lesson number four, this is a
very

00:45:25.320 --> 00:45:30.240
specific one.

00:45:27.199 --> 00:45:33.919
If you are pregnant and go into labor

00:45:32.400 --> 00:45:38.586
at school, okay?

00:45:35.000 --> 00:45:40.606
Just call Trisha LaHam. [cheering]

00:45:40.639 --> 00:45:45.719
Right?

00:45:42.559 --> 00:45:47.799
Luckily, the baby came late, and I'm

00:45:45.719 --> 00:45:51.440
just going to say Cole, who was supposed
to be here to help me tonight, uh

00:45:50.376 --> 00:45:54.240
[laughter] late again.

00:45:54.360 --> 00:46:00.160
All right. Oh, and the same goes for if

00:45:56.320 --> 00:46:02.640
there's a pandemic, just call Trisha.

00:46:00.159 --> 00:46:05.920
Number five,

00:46:02.639 --> 00:46:07.799
do what is right, not what is easy.

00:46:05.920 --> 00:46:10.680
Thank you to Vicky Milstein for my daily

00:46:07.800 --> 00:46:14.800
reminder of that.

00:46:10.679 --> 00:46:16.879
Fairness and inclusion take ongoing

00:46:14.800 --> 00:46:20.120
hard work.

00:46:16.880 --> 00:46:23.480
It is better for everyone

00:46:20.119 --> 00:46:28.279
and it is necessary work.

00:46:23.480 --> 00:46:32.840
Please support programs like Scholars

00:46:28.280 --> 00:46:35.760
and Seed, METCO, and materials fee

00:46:32.840 --> 00:46:37.480
and Steps to Success.

00:46:35.760 --> 00:46:39.920
All right? And

00:46:40.719 --> 00:46:46.519
Lastly, while taking care of children,

00:46:45.039 --> 00:46:49.599
take care of each other.

00:46:46.519 --> 00:46:52.880
I will try not to get emotional now.

00:46:49.599 --> 00:46:56.000
Teaching is a deeply personal job.

00:46:52.880 --> 00:46:58.519
Colleagues become friends.

00:46:56.000 --> 00:47:00.679
I look around this room and I see many
friends.

00:46:58.519 --> 00:47:04.679
We've shared in weddings and births.

00:47:03.079 --> 00:47:09.559
We've helped each other through hard times
and loss.

00:47:06.880 --> 00:47:13.720
And maybe most importantly, we have

00:47:09.559 --> 00:47:15.639
found laughter and joy in this wonderful

00:47:13.719 --> 00:47:19.456
job of teaching.

00:47:15.639 --> 00:47:21.476
For this, I am thankful. Thank you.

00:47:19.456 --> 00:47:21.476
[Applause]

00:47:25.800 --> 00:47:30.720
Thank you, Lisa. Paul Larreau Priestley.

00:47:36.559 --> 00:47:42.359
Hello everyone. I'm Paul Larreau
Priestley. I run the

00:47:40.679 --> 00:47:43.679
Graphic Arts Copy Center at Brookline

00:47:42.360 --> 00:47:48.079
High School.

00:47:43.679 --> 00:47:50.519
I have been there for 31 years.

00:47:48.079 --> 00:47:54.199
That's a long time, but I still have more
to give.

00:47:52.800 --> 00:47:58.359
As I thought about what to say this

00:47:57.079 --> 00:48:01.559
evening,

00:47:58.360 --> 00:48:04.240
I considered how to use

00:48:01.559 --> 00:48:06.639
this time well.

00:48:04.239 --> 00:48:09.919
Should I talk about fighting

00:48:06.639 --> 00:48:12.359
the systemic racism in our schools

00:48:09.920 --> 00:48:16.240
and the larger community around us?

00:48:14.480 --> 00:48:21.159
Or should I talk about how we have

00:48:19.079 --> 00:48:24.679
worked to improve

00:48:21.159 --> 00:48:28.759
racial diversity in our classrooms,

00:48:24.679 --> 00:48:31.079
among our staff, and in our
administration?

00:48:28.760 --> 00:48:33.120
Then I thought, "What about

00:48:31.079 --> 00:48:35.799
financial equity?

00:48:33.119 --> 00:48:39.239
Financial equity is also important. But

00:48:35.800 --> 00:48:42.760
then guess what? I said, 'No.'"

00:48:39.239 --> 00:48:44.039
I said, "Love."

00:48:42.760 --> 00:48:49.360
Love. Love is powerful.

00:48:46.639 --> 00:48:52.839
Love helps people heal.

00:48:49.360 --> 00:48:56.880
Love supports each other.

00:48:52.840 --> 00:49:00.640
We give love to every student

00:48:56.880 --> 00:49:00.640
through the power of knowledge.

00:49:01.000 --> 00:49:06.719
We help and support each other in many
ways.

00:49:03.840 --> 00:49:08.680
This gives us all the help we need.

00:49:06.719 --> 00:49:12.839
And that is a very nice thing.

00:49:11.679 --> 00:49:18.640
I think of all of you as my friends.

00:49:17.159 --> 00:49:22.920
In these times,

00:49:20.800 --> 00:49:27.600
people need

00:49:22.920 --> 00:49:30.240
nothing more than love.

00:49:27.599 --> 00:49:34.480
My last words might make

00:49:30.239 --> 00:49:36.919
some of you feel uneasy.

00:49:34.480 --> 00:49:41.159
But I want you all

00:49:39.519 --> 00:49:44.519
to know that I truly

00:49:43.280 --> 00:49:48.800
care for each one of you.

00:49:47.360 --> 00:49:53.360
In our world,

00:49:50.519 --> 00:49:57.199
people can share hate

00:49:53.360 --> 00:50:01.599
and negativity with strangers.

00:49:57.199 --> 00:50:05.199
But I choose to share love.

00:50:01.599 --> 00:50:10.639
Remember this: lead with love, because

00:50:05.199 --> 00:50:10.639
love will win in the end.

00:50:11.068 --> 00:50:13.088
[applause]

00:50:17.639 --> 00:50:21.279
Thank you, Paul. Susan Lipman.

00:50:24.168 --> 00:50:26.188
[applause]

00:50:29.440 --> 00:50:34.119
Thank you for having us here tonight.

00:50:32.440 --> 00:50:37.000
I am very proud to be here with this

00:50:34.119 --> 00:50:39.559
group of friends, which includes my

00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:41.480
children's teachers, my children's
classmates' parents, and also

00:50:39.559 --> 00:50:46.000
some people I went to Brookline High with.

00:50:44.360 --> 00:50:49.000
Not many can say they had the same job for
31 years, and

00:50:47.320 --> 00:50:54.159
33 years if you count my year as a
substitute teacher and special education assistant

00:50:52.239 --> 00:50:57.839
before that.

00:50:56.119 --> 00:50:59.880
Even fewer people can say they

00:50:57.840 --> 00:51:03.600
really enjoy going to work every day.

00:50:59.880 --> 00:51:05.519
Pierce School has been a big part

00:51:03.599 --> 00:51:08.360
of my life since I was 6 years old.

00:51:05.519 --> 00:51:10.639
I went to the new Pierce School as

00:51:08.360 --> 00:51:13.840
a first grader in 1975.

00:51:10.639 --> 00:51:16.119
I went to school there for all of
elementary.

00:51:13.840 --> 00:51:18.240
I made some of my best

00:51:16.119 --> 00:51:20.880
friends during those years.

00:51:18.239 --> 00:51:23.279
My mother later taught Chapter 1, also
called Title 1; they kept changing the name.

00:51:20.880 --> 00:51:27.160
My mother later taught Chapter 1 or Title
1, they kept kind of changing the

00:51:25.079 --> 00:51:32.000
I started at Pierce School after I could
no longer teach at St.

00:51:30.119 --> 00:51:34.799
Mary's School where I taught for many
years.

00:51:32.000 --> 00:51:37.719
Later, my kids and stepkids also went to
Pierce.

00:51:34.800 --> 00:51:41.719
My journey in Brookline started in 1993

00:51:39.599 --> 00:51:46.279
when Barbara Shay hired me

00:51:43.679 --> 00:51:49.519
as a substitute teacher at Lincoln School.

00:51:46.280 --> 00:51:51.440
Barbara was amazing.

00:51:49.519 --> 00:51:54.200
At that time, I was working on my master's
degree.

00:51:52.719 --> 00:51:58.159
My first year was at the old Lincoln
School. Now I am back there as a teacher at Pierce School.

00:51:56.559 --> 00:52:02.639
The next year we moved to the new Lincoln
School, but it was also called the old school.

00:52:00.360 --> 00:52:05.879
I moved with them and worked in the
learning center while I got my master's.

00:52:04.679 --> 00:52:10.320
The following year Chris Field, who was my
third-grade teacher, hired me as a second- grade teacher at Pierce School.

00:52:07.960 --> 00:52:14.080
That felt like another full circle moment.

00:52:12.920 --> 00:52:18.239
Over the past 31 years, I have learned
from great teachers and now I teach amazing educators.

00:52:15.920 --> 00:52:22.559
When I started at Pierce, I worked with
teachers who had taught me.

00:52:19.800 --> 00:52:26.719
They greatly influenced who I am today as
a person and a teacher.

00:52:24.119 --> 00:52:30.879
Marie Lavelle, who I miss very much, was
like a mom to me.

00:52:29.039 --> 00:52:34.800
She supported me from the beginning, and
now I try to be like her for my students and fellow teachers.

00:52:32.599 --> 00:52:38.639
Pierce is more than just a job. It is my
community. It holds my childhood memories and is where my children thrived.

00:52:34.800 --> 00:52:41.720
This year, I have a student in my second-
grade class whose aunt was in my first class at Pierce.

00:52:38.639 --> 00:52:45.480
Her mother was in class with my stepson
and also Suzanne's son.

00:52:44.039 --> 00:52:49.559
Being a teacher, a mom, and an...

00:52:47.360 --> 00:52:51.720
alongside colleagues who had been my

00:52:49.559 --> 00:52:54.639
teachers when I went there.

00:52:51.719 --> 00:52:57.759
They all had such a huge impact on the

00:52:54.639 --> 00:53:00.159
person and the teacher that I am today.

00:52:57.760 --> 00:53:03.040
Marie Lavelle who I miss so greatly

00:53:00.159 --> 00:53:05.440
every day was my work mom. She took me

00:53:03.039 --> 00:53:09.079
under her wing from day one and now as
someone who's been at Pierce

00:53:07.360 --> 00:53:14.279
for a long time I really try and emulate
her guidance,

00:53:12.039 --> 00:53:17.199
her patience and her love to all the

00:53:14.280 --> 00:53:19.040
teachers and the children.

00:53:17.199 --> 00:53:23.360
Pierce is more than a job for me. It's my
community. The place that holds my

00:53:21.320 --> 00:53:27.840
childhood memories and the place where my
own children thrived.

00:53:25.800 --> 00:53:32.600
This year I have a child in my second
grade class whose mother was in my first

00:53:30.719 --> 00:53:35.759
class I'm sorry, whose aunt was in my

00:53:32.599 --> 00:53:39.559
first class at Pierce and whose mother

00:53:35.760 --> 00:53:42.920
was in class with my stepson and also a

00:53:39.559 --> 00:53:46.119
Suzanne's too. Um

00:53:42.920 --> 00:53:48.920
Um being a being a teacher, a mom, an

00:53:46.119 --> 00:53:52.840
A person who went to school here and lives
in Brookline has made it to this point.

00:53:51.440 --> 00:53:58.240
I have done many jobs over the years.

00:53:55.480 --> 00:54:00.960
But I would not change anything at all.

00:53:58.239 --> 00:54:04.079
I enjoy every moment of it.

00:54:00.960 --> 00:54:06.360
I love walking down the street.

00:54:04.079 --> 00:54:11.039
I get hugs from people who are 30 years
old.

00:54:09.320 --> 00:54:14.360
And also from kids who are seven years
old.

00:54:11.039 --> 00:54:17.440
I love seeing a Brookline police officer.

00:54:14.360 --> 00:54:19.440
Then I remember that police officer was in
my second grade class.

00:54:17.440 --> 00:54:22.400
I still love being a part of the school I
entered as a first grader long ago.

00:54:19.440 --> 00:54:25.000
I want to say well done to everyone for
these 30 or 31 years.

00:54:22.400 --> 00:54:28.119
Not every day is easy, especially at this
time of the year.

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:30.079
We are all trying to get through to the
end,

00:54:28.119 --> 00:54:34.440
but for those of us who have been here a
long time,

00:54:31.760 --> 00:54:38.559
we know how special the community of
Brookline is.

00:54:36.280 --> 00:54:41.080
So, thank you very much for having us all.

00:54:38.559 --> 00:54:43.552
[applause]

00:54:41.079 --> 00:54:45.572
Thank you, Susan. Now, Stephanie Poon.

00:54:43.552 --> 00:54:45.572
[applause]

00:54:49.440 --> 00:54:53.280
Thank you for this wonderful event.

00:54:54.032 --> 00:54:56.052
It is a joy to listen to all of you.

00:55:02.000 --> 00:55:07.400
I have been thinking about two things
before tonight.

00:55:04.280 --> 00:55:09.200
What has helped me for 30 years? That is a
long time.

00:55:07.400 --> 00:55:13.439
And what have I noticed about changes and
things that have stayed the same since I started at Brookline High School in the 1990s?

00:55:11.559 --> 00:55:16.960
Here is what I found out.

00:55:15.639 --> 00:55:21.400
The things that have made this job
possible and sometimes even enjoyable are the people around me at Brookline High School.

00:55:18.840 --> 00:55:23.200
These are my students, which are my first
priority.

00:55:21.400 --> 00:55:26.440
Even when they ask me questions about
things I just said, They truly keep me going.

00:55:27.039 --> 00:55:29.960
They are very curious, frustrating, funny,
smart, hardworking,

00:55:28.800 --> 00:55:33.920
and they always make me think about how I
can do my job better.

00:55:31.559 --> 00:55:36.799
This time of year makes me really believe
that next year,

00:55:33.920 --> 00:55:39.720
I will figure out how to do this job well
and fix all the education problems.

00:55:36.800 --> 00:55:42.959
students first and foremost, um who,
though they might ask me a question

00:55:41.039 --> 00:55:45.880
about something I have literally just

00:55:42.960 --> 00:55:48.840
said, are truly the reason I keep going.

00:55:45.880 --> 00:55:51.559
They are endlessly curious, maddening,

00:55:48.840 --> 00:55:54.840
silly, smart, hard working, and constantly
make me think about how I can

00:55:53.320 --> 00:55:58.840
do my job better. This is the time of year
when I really

00:55:56.480 --> 00:56:02.600
lean into the thought that next year, I
will in fact figure out how to do this

00:56:00.559 --> 00:56:06.599
job and solve all the problems of
education.

00:56:05.159 --> 00:56:09.480
The other people around me at Brookline
High that make this possible are my

00:56:07.880 --> 00:56:12.760
friends. I love them.

00:56:10.800 --> 00:56:17.000
If I didn't have such smart, caring people
around me, I would go

00:56:14.440 --> 00:56:20.119
crazy and quit. The other thing that has
made this

00:56:18.440 --> 00:56:25.119
30-year journey possible is all the things
I've been able to do.

00:56:23.000 --> 00:56:28.519
I've helped new teachers at Brookline for
years through the Teachers Mentoring

00:56:26.599 --> 00:56:33.159
Teachers program. When a group of my
experienced colleagues

00:56:30.519 --> 00:56:37.119
talked for the 15th time about how broken
ninth grade history was, and how unhappy we were with the unfair

00:56:35.239 --> 00:56:41.880
student grouping that led to 70% of our
students taking honors, we, along with

00:56:39.639 --> 00:56:46.280
the Office of Teaching and Learning, the
Superintendent, and the School Committee (the elected board that runs the public schools),

00:56:44.840 --> 00:56:50.440
created WISP. When another group of
colleagues

00:56:48.519 --> 00:56:53.639
talked about the senioritis that affects
our second semester seniors,

00:56:51.840 --> 00:56:57.400
and how their only interest in school
seemed to be their

00:56:55.880 --> 00:57:01.320
grades instead of their learning, we
created a hands-on senior class

00:56:59.079 --> 00:57:05.400
called EPIC. Giving teachers chances to
use our

00:57:03.840 --> 00:57:09.920
lots of experience and training to create

00:57:07.519 --> 00:57:12.679
new things and solve problems keeps us
going.

00:57:09.920 --> 00:57:16.319
I was also supported because I got to see
my own children go through

00:57:14.880 --> 00:57:20.120
Brookline schools, and there is nothing so
grounding as seeing your child benefit from your colleagues' hard work,

00:57:17.920 --> 00:57:24.359
to feel the love and care given to them,
and know that you can never really pay it back, only

00:57:22.920 --> 00:57:28.120
forward. The materials fee program that
allowed

00:57:26.719 --> 00:57:32.359
my husband and I to send our children,

00:57:30.559 --> 00:57:35.680
one of whom is right back there,

00:57:33.840 --> 00:57:38.720
through the Public Schools of Brookline
(PSB) gave me a stronger sense of commitment to this place. As my

00:57:35.679 --> 00:57:40.919
husband Brian Lee recently said, it
literally meant that I had a personal stake in

00:57:38.719 --> 00:57:44.639
the school. Do I want to make my school
the best it can be, to devote myself to my

00:57:42.960 --> 00:57:47.199
students the way that my colleagues did
for my two children?

00:57:46.079 --> 00:57:52.199
Absolutely. So, the second thing that I've
been

00:57:50.440 --> 00:57:56.039
thinking about is what has changed and
what has stayed the same.

00:57:53.760 --> 00:57:59.360
And really the first two points from
earlier about the students and the colleagues,

00:57:57.159 --> 00:58:03.160
those haven't changed. I mean, they
literally have changed. They're

00:58:01.760 --> 00:58:08.280
different people. But the spirit, the
energy, the

00:58:06.559 --> 00:58:12.560
inspiration, and the fun, that's pretty
similar.

00:58:09.559 --> 00:58:16.400
Lots of things have changed, of course.

00:58:14.159 --> 00:58:19.880
When I started, I had binders filled with
lesson plans, and I wrote on a chalkboard.

00:58:17.599 --> 00:58:21.759
I spent a lot of time just

00:58:19.880 --> 00:58:26.640
trying to learn all the things I needed

00:58:26.800 --> 00:58:29.720
to teach, acting and teaching.

00:58:28.159 --> 00:58:34.719
trying to learn all the things I needed

00:58:29.719 --> 00:58:37.359
to teach, acting and teaching.

00:58:34.719 --> 00:58:40.319
The students were themselves,

00:58:37.360 --> 00:58:42.400
but less worried.

00:58:40.320 --> 00:58:45.960
It seemed like teachers got more respect.

00:58:46.679 --> 00:58:53.039
The things that help me are not hard or
strange.

00:58:50.800 --> 00:58:55.400
They are the things that help all of us.

00:58:53.039 --> 00:58:57.920
Important work with nice people,

00:58:55.400 --> 00:59:01.720
new challenges that are interesting,

00:58:57.920 --> 00:59:05.720
fun, laughter, and sometimes happiness,

00:59:01.719 --> 00:59:08.230
and summer vacation. [applause]

00:59:11.079 --> 00:59:15.440
Thank you, Steph. Now, is this Malia or
Malia?

00:59:14.960 --> 00:59:21.329
Malia. Malia Scott. Thank you.

00:59:19.309 --> 00:59:21.329
[applause]

00:59:28.079 --> 00:59:33.400
At our last math specialist meeting, we
talked about

00:59:31.159 --> 00:59:35.759
turning our careers in Brookline

00:59:33.400 --> 00:59:38.960
into years, days, hours, and minutes,

00:59:35.760 --> 00:59:40.920
because we have fun with math like that.

00:59:38.960 --> 00:59:44.480
So,

00:59:43.320 --> 00:59:46.960
please allow me to share.

00:59:44.480 --> 00:59:50.800
Thirty-two years ago, when I started my

00:59:46.960 --> 00:59:52.800
master's program and full-year training at
the Lincoln School,

00:59:50.800 --> 00:59:57.360
I didn't know what the materials fee
program was,

00:59:55.400 --> 01:00:01.880
or how much it would change my family's
life.

01:00:00.199 --> 01:00:05.800
A week and a half ago, I got up on stage
and graduated my youngest from

01:00:03.199 --> 01:00:10.160
Brookline High. I feel very thankful for
the wonderful

01:00:08.079 --> 01:00:14.440
education my children got here in
Brookline.

01:00:12.559 --> 01:00:18.159
Even though my three children, one of whom
is over there,

01:00:15.719 --> 01:00:22.719
are very different learners,

01:00:19.760 --> 01:00:25.320
they all did well, were challenged, and

01:00:22.719 --> 01:00:27.639
had great teachers that

01:00:25.320 --> 01:00:30.160
helped them reach their potential.

01:00:27.639 --> 01:00:32.599
I am very grateful that the materials fee

01:00:30.159 --> 01:00:35.559
program made this all possible,

01:00:32.599 --> 01:00:38.000
as it not only helped my family, but also
let me dedicate my

01:00:35.559 --> 01:00:41.719
work life to the Brookline community.

01:00:39.760 --> 01:00:46.679
5,856 school days ago,

01:00:44.159 --> 01:00:50.119
I could never have imagined I would spend
most of my work life as

01:00:48.360 --> 01:00:55.159
a math specialist, since books and reading
have always been my lifelong

01:00:52.400 --> 01:00:58.639
interest. However, during my early time in

01:00:57.119 --> 01:01:02.400
Brookline, I was lucky to work with such
skilled and gifted

01:01:00.719 --> 01:01:07.639
Brookline, I had the privilege of
partnering with such skilled and gifted

01:01:04.760 --> 01:01:10.640
math teachers like Rose Christiansen,

01:01:07.639 --> 01:01:12.759
Nancy Buel, and Hillary Pastor.

01:01:10.639 --> 01:01:16.760
They helped me change how I see myself as
a math teacher.

01:01:15.360 --> 01:01:20.640
They encouraged me to keep learning and
improving my teaching.

01:01:19.280 --> 01:01:25.719
Most importantly, they showed me the true

01:01:22.920 --> 01:01:28.519
joy of teaching math.

01:01:25.719 --> 01:01:32.559
They taught me that every student can
learn math.

01:01:31.320 --> 01:01:36.679
My job as a math specialist focuses on
working with others.

01:01:34.519 --> 01:01:38.920
I feel very lucky to work with teachers
who love to learn.

01:01:36.679 --> 01:01:41.759
They help, challenge, and inspire me to
grow.

01:01:38.920 --> 01:01:43.880
It has been a real privilege to work with
such smart teachers.

01:01:41.760 --> 01:01:48.160
We find creative ways to make math
exciting.

01:01:46.239 --> 01:01:51.399
They encourage me to try new things and
push my limits.

01:01:49.760 --> 01:01:55.960
I am very proud of what we have achieved
together over the years.

01:01:53.599 --> 01:01:59.480
38,064 school hours ago, I did not see how
important a supportive school leader was.

01:01:57.880 --> 01:02:04.679
Today, I am very thankful to have worked
with great principals

01:02:02.360 --> 01:02:09.159
like Barbara Shay, Andrew Bott, and now
Brian Dinitzio.

01:02:06.920 --> 01:02:13.359
They have shown great trust in me.

01:02:11.440 --> 01:02:16.360
By supporting my math projects at Lincoln,

01:02:13.360 --> 01:02:19.240
they have given me the time and space to
be creative, try new ideas, and grow as a math teacher.

01:02:16.360 --> 01:02:22.719
And finally, 2,283,840 school minutes ago,

01:02:20.760 --> 01:02:26.279
I could not have imagined that the joy I
felt when I first worked with students would still be

01:02:24.639 --> 01:02:31.440
central to my teaching today.

01:02:29.159 --> 01:02:33.639
I love being a teacher.

01:02:31.440 --> 01:02:38.079
I enjoy breaking the "I am bad at math"
mindset and feel happy knowing

01:02:33.639 --> 01:02:38.079
each student is unique with their own
strengths and challenges.

01:02:39.480 --> 01:02:45.079
In education, there is no one right way
for everyone.

01:02:43.079 --> 01:02:48.960
To help our most needy students, I must
always learn and improve.

01:02:47.239 --> 01:02:52.599
I look forward to those hard-fought
moments

01:02:48.960 --> 01:02:55.119
when a tough idea finally makes sense

01:02:52.599 --> 01:02:59.480
and the boost of confidence when

01:02:58.079 --> 01:03:04.480
students start to see themselves as good
problem solvers.

01:03:01.599 --> 01:03:07.480
challenges. In education, there is never

01:03:04.480 --> 01:03:11.039
a one-size-fits-all approach. To meet the
needs of our most vulnerable

01:03:09.000 --> 01:03:16.000
students, I must constantly grow, reflect,
and learn.

01:03:13.440 --> 01:03:19.480
I live for those hard-fought aha moments

01:03:16.000 --> 01:03:21.360
when a complex concept finally clicks

01:03:19.480 --> 01:03:23.519
and the sudden surge of confidence when

01:03:21.360 --> 01:03:26.599
students begin to recognize themselves

01:03:23.519 --> 01:03:29.320
as capable problem solvers.

01:03:26.599 --> 01:03:32.920
I feel very lucky to still be a teacher in
Brookline.

01:03:33.280 --> 01:03:39.349
30,400.

01:03:35.559 --> 01:03:41.369
Seconds later. Thank you.

01:03:39.349 --> 01:03:41.369
[applause]

01:03:46.159 --> 01:03:51.480
Thank you, Malia. I want to remind people
who are still standing that there

01:03:49.639 --> 01:03:56.240
are three seats here and more seats over
there on my left. So,

01:03:54.360 --> 01:03:57.039
why don't you sit down?

01:03:56.239 --> 01:04:02.273
We will be here a little longer.

01:03:58.519 --> 01:04:04.293
Okay, next up is Yasmin Shariff.

01:04:02.273 --> 01:04:04.293
[applause]

01:04:07.280 --> 01:04:09.760
All right.

01:04:10.920 --> 01:04:17.440
Lisa needs to put her glasses on. I have
to take mine off because that’s what’s happening. Um before I start, I want to thank the

01:04:15.000 --> 01:04:19.840
School Committee (the elected board that
runs the public schools) for this. This is great and thank all of you for being here.

01:04:18.639 --> 01:04:24.559
I want to thank my husband who often says,
"I don’t know why this takes you so long. You have been teaching for so many years." But as all the

01:04:22.960 --> 01:04:28.799
teachers in the room know, no matter how

01:04:27.039 --> 01:04:32.960
long you’ve been teaching, the time

01:04:30.920 --> 01:04:35.360
does not get less. It just keeps

01:04:32.960 --> 01:04:38.519
on going. Um I also want to thank the

01:04:35.360 --> 01:04:40.160
many parents here whose kids I taught
thanks to the materials fee

01:04:38.519 --> 01:04:45.279
program we heard about tonight. That made
me a part of this

01:04:43.079 --> 01:04:48.560
community. My friends are Brookline
parents. My child has Brookline friends.

01:04:47.360 --> 01:04:52.039
My child went through Baker School and
Brookline High School (BHS) and

01:04:50.440 --> 01:04:57.199
I taught many of your kids. I taught
Nicole's kids. I taught Lisa's kids. I taught Trisha's kids. I taught

01:04:55.039 --> 01:05:01.159
Susan's kids. I mean, I taught a lot of
kids here.

01:04:59.599 --> 01:05:05.199
So, I’ve taught many families here and it
really connects us to the

01:05:02.840 --> 01:05:09.039
community. I want to highlight the
materials fee program because it is a special

01:05:06.840 --> 01:05:12.039
program that keeps us here and makes us
really dedicated to this

01:05:10.719 --> 01:05:16.480
community. I have a story that

01:05:13.920 --> 01:05:20.079
starts at the beginning of my teaching and
ends today.

01:05:17.800 --> 01:05:23.920
Um I started student teaching in 1995, so
I am kind of a mix of 30 and 31 years now.

01:05:21.639 --> 01:05:26.519
I got my full-time job in January.

01:05:25.320 --> 01:05:30.920
So, I’ve been teaching for about 30 and a
half years, I guess.

01:05:29.239 --> 01:05:34.039
But, I want to share a story about my
first moments as a teacher. I started student teaching in the fifth grade at

01:05:33.199 --> 01:05:38.559
Baker School in the fall of 1995.

01:05:36.440 --> 01:05:42.719
of a combo cuz I started teaching student
teaching in 1995

01:05:41.119 --> 01:05:45.279
and I got my full-time job in January.

01:05:42.719 --> 01:05:48.080
So, I'm like 30 and a half years in, I
guess.

01:05:47.000 --> 01:05:52.119
But, I wanted to tell a story that
happened the the very first moments of

01:05:50.559 --> 01:05:57.119
my teaching career. So, I started student
teaching in the fifth grade at

01:05:53.679 --> 01:05:59.559
Baker School in the fall of 1995.

01:05:57.119 --> 01:06:03.279
I loved Baker School, the community, and
everything about teaching.

01:06:01.400 --> 01:06:07.720
When a teacher in the sixth grade was let
go at Thanksgiving, I applied for the sixth grade job and hoped for the best.

01:06:05.079 --> 01:06:11.759
I knew the sixth grade class was hard and
that my principal, Tom Cavanaugh, wanted an experienced teacher.

01:06:09.760 --> 01:06:15.800
The interview committee had my principal,
the vice principal, a teacher, and five parents from the homeroom class.

01:06:13.760 --> 01:06:20.080
This was my very first interview and it
was really scary.

01:06:18.280 --> 01:06:24.039
But I thought, if nothing else, it was
good practice for a future job.

01:06:22.159 --> 01:06:28.400
So, I did the interview and I went home
for winter break.

01:06:26.679 --> 01:06:32.320
About a week later, I got a call from Mr.
Cavanaugh.

01:06:29.960 --> 01:06:36.680
He told me that the parents in the
interview committee really wanted to hire me.

01:06:35.039 --> 01:06:41.119
Then he said, "It's against my better
judgment, but I’m offering you the sixth grade position."

01:06:38.440 --> 01:06:42.639
I was so excited and promised him I would
work hard to do a good job.

01:06:41.119 --> 01:06:47.359
Tom was right to want an experienced
teacher because starting in January was really hard.

01:06:44.480 --> 01:06:52.119
There were many behavior issues and
different learning needs in the sixth grade and especially in my homeroom.

01:06:47.360 --> 01:06:54.039
The students were also feeling bad about
themselves.

01:06:52.119 --> 01:06:56.800
The first thing they said to me when I
walked in was that I was going to hate their class.

01:06:57.161 --> 01:07:01.920
It was terrible.

01:07:00.239 --> 01:07:05.720
They said all the teachers hated their
class and I would hate them too.

01:07:04.119 --> 01:07:10.119
I looked around and told them, "You are my
first class. I will love you."

01:07:07.239 --> 01:07:12.479
And we will have a great rest of the year.

01:07:10.119 --> 01:07:16.440
But I worried a lot in my mind.

01:07:14.840 --> 01:07:20.800
I was 23, I looked about 15, and I had
never been in a classroom alone.

01:07:18.480 --> 01:07:23.600
I called home many nights that year,
worried about the classroom behaviors and wondering if I was helping the kids.

01:07:22.119 --> 01:07:28.599
My mom, a former teacher, kept saying, "If
you can get through this year, you can get through anything."

01:07:26.159 --> 01:07:30.639
So, I kept trying, showing my students I
cared, that they were capable, and hoping to bring positivity to the room.

01:07:28.599 --> 01:07:32.159
I know, it was terrible.

01:07:30.639 --> 01:07:36.559
They said all the teachers hated their
class and I was going to hate them, too.

01:07:35.159 --> 01:07:41.960
I remember looking around the room and
saying to them, "You're my very first

01:07:38.480 --> 01:07:43.679
class. I'm going to love you." And we're

01:07:41.960 --> 01:07:47.440
going to have a great rest of the year.

01:07:43.679 --> 01:07:51.440
But in my mind, I was worried.

01:07:47.440 --> 01:07:54.240
I was 23. I looked about 15 and I was

01:07:51.440 --> 01:07:56.079
untested in a classroom by myself.

01:07:54.239 --> 01:07:59.759
I remember calling home to stop bending
nights that year, worried about all the

01:07:58.119 --> 01:08:03.280
classroom behaviors I was struggling with
and wondering if I was getting

01:08:01.360 --> 01:08:05.400
through to these kids at all.

01:08:03.280 --> 01:08:08.519
My mom, a former teacher, just kept saying
to me, "If you can get through

01:08:07.119 --> 01:08:11.519
this year, you can get through anything."

01:08:09.679 --> 01:08:15.119
So, I kept plugging away, letting my
students know how much I cared about

01:08:13.119 --> 01:08:19.199
them, how capable they were, and hoping to
create some positivity in the room

01:08:17.640 --> 01:08:22.159
from the negativity that had greeted me at
the start.

01:08:20.600 --> 01:08:26.239
As the year was ending, I heard noise in
the hallway.

01:08:23.680 --> 01:08:27.640
That is never a good sign.

01:08:26.239 --> 01:08:31.600
I left the room to check if everything was
okay, but what I heard made me stop.

01:08:29.359 --> 01:08:35.120
Some kids in another class were teasing
kids in my class.

01:08:33.279 --> 01:08:36.960
The kids in my class replied,

01:08:35.119 --> 01:08:40.399
"Oh, yeah? We are the smart class."

01:08:36.960 --> 01:08:42.359
I felt a bit emotional and very happy.

01:08:40.399 --> 01:08:45.400
We had come from a place where students
did not feel good about themselves.

01:08:44.199 --> 01:08:49.199
They thought everyone disliked them.

01:08:47.520 --> 01:08:53.079
Now, they felt like a group of smart and
important kids, which they were.

01:08:50.798 --> 01:08:54.479
This memory reminds me how important it is
for kids to feel valuable and loved in school.

01:08:53.079 --> 01:08:59.239
Today, 31 years later, I am still happily
at Baker in the same job I started in 1995.

01:08:56.239 --> 01:09:01.719
Teachers are hired to teach subjects and
help students grow.

01:08:59.239 --> 01:09:03.798
But one of the most important lessons I
learned happened in my first 6 months of teaching.

01:09:01.720 --> 01:09:08.079
If students do not feel seen, cared for,
or valued, they will not learn well.

01:09:06.838 --> 01:09:12.720
As I think about retiring soon,

01:09:10.560 --> 01:09:17.119
I remember the almost 2,500 Brookline
students I have taught.

01:09:14.479 --> 01:09:20.399
They might not remember everything about
cells,

01:09:18.600 --> 01:09:24.798
but I hope they remember I cared about
them, believed in them,

01:09:22.798 --> 01:09:26.720
and that their curiosity, strength, and
voice are important.

01:09:24.798 --> 01:09:29.119
[applause]

01:09:26.720 --> 01:09:32.480
Thank you, Esme.

01:09:29.119 --> 01:09:34.239
Tom Cavana was a very smart man.

01:09:32.479 --> 01:09:36.879
He made great choices about teachers.

01:09:34.239 --> 01:09:39.679
Okay, Francesca Stark. [applause]

01:09:36.880 --> 01:09:41.838
Hi everyone.

01:09:39.680 --> 01:09:46.359
I am Francesca Stark.

01:09:44.159 --> 01:09:50.160
I wanted to say I agree with everything
everyone has said.

01:09:51.393 --> 01:09:53.413
That’s all for me.

01:09:57.119 --> 01:10:02.439
Still, I was thinking about why I chose
Brookline, why I stayed here, and what I hope for Brookline.

01:09:58.720 --> 01:10:05.119
Tom Cavana, he was a very smart guy.

01:10:02.439 --> 01:10:08.879
Made very good decisions on teachers.

01:10:05.119 --> 01:10:11.098
Okay, Francesca Stark. [applause]

01:10:16.920 --> 01:10:22.960
Hi everybody. Um

01:10:18.880 --> 01:10:25.560
So, I'm Francesca Stark, and I um

01:10:22.960 --> 01:10:28.520
wanted to say I everything everybody

01:10:25.560 --> 01:10:31.600
already said, so that's it.

01:10:28.520 --> 01:10:34.160
Pretty much though. Um I was thinking

01:10:31.600 --> 01:10:38.239
about why I came to Brookline, why I
stayed in Brookline, and what I hope for

01:10:37.079 --> 01:10:42.079
Brookline.

01:10:38.239 --> 01:10:44.880
I came to Brookline because my mom

01:10:42.079 --> 01:10:47.640
was a struggling painter, and

01:10:44.880 --> 01:10:51.240
she couldn't pay for my braces, so she

01:10:49.680 --> 01:10:54.800
decided to become a teacher. She

01:10:53.600 --> 01:10:58.960
heard about the Brookline schools, which
we have heard many times.

01:10:56.800 --> 01:11:03.560
So, we moved to Westbourne Terrace to a

01:11:00.800 --> 01:11:05.480
rent-controlled apartment, and I went to
Driscoll School.

01:11:03.560 --> 01:11:08.880
There was a group that had

01:11:05.479 --> 01:11:11.079
guidance counselors for everything then,

01:11:08.880 --> 01:11:15.439
including children of single moms.

01:11:13.359 --> 01:11:18.279
There was a guidance counselor who had
little rubber dolls

01:11:17.239 --> 01:11:22.159
that we could use to act out some kind of
trauma.

01:11:20.439 --> 01:11:26.800
I don’t know what they were for, but we
acted them out. And later when I got hired in

01:11:24.119 --> 01:11:28.800
Brookline, I thought, "Oh, I am one of the
little rubber dolls now."

01:11:26.800 --> 01:11:32.880
There was a firefighter rubber doll and

01:11:28.800 --> 01:11:34.239
a nurse rubber doll, and I went to

01:11:32.880 --> 01:11:39.880
school. So, I had a very good experience
at Driscoll.

01:11:37.760 --> 01:11:43.880
I had a very bad fourth-grade

01:11:39.880 --> 01:11:45.520
teacher who would mock kids in the class.

01:11:43.880 --> 01:11:49.360
I always wanted to be a teacher, not
really because of her, but I wanted to

01:11:46.920 --> 01:11:52.239
be a teacher that was different from her.

01:11:49.359 --> 01:11:55.359
My mom told me, "Don't ever become a

01:11:54.000 --> 01:12:00.119
teacher." After she was a painter, she
became a teacher.

01:11:57.640 --> 01:12:01.800
She said, "They will not trust your
intelligence.

01:12:00.119 --> 01:12:06.880
They will not let you do art. You will
never be

01:12:04.760 --> 01:12:10.360
free to be who you are. You must

01:12:06.880 --> 01:12:12.279
follow a structured plan. Don't do it."

01:12:10.359 --> 01:12:15.960
I immediately decided to do

01:12:12.279 --> 01:12:19.119
it anyway. So, I became a teacher, and

01:12:15.960 --> 01:12:22.680
wait, I wasn't sure what to do, and I was
walking down the

01:12:20.720 --> 01:12:27.039
Fenway, and I passed Wheelock College, and
I saw a sign that said,

01:12:25.680 --> 01:12:30.279
"Come join the Learning Teaching
Collaborative, where teachers can be

01:12:28.640 --> 01:12:34.599
leaders." I thought, "My mom would like
that." So, that's how I ended up there.

01:12:32.560 --> 01:12:36.320
I walked in, and a woman named Joan Gatto
said,

01:12:34.600 --> 01:12:41.519
"Did you hear about the job opening, the
intern opening?"

01:12:39.640 --> 01:12:44.000
I said, "No." So, it was to

01:12:41.520 --> 01:12:46.040
be an intern for someone named Vivian

01:12:44.000 --> 01:12:49.880
Troen at the former Devotion School, and I
was lucky to

01:12:46.039 --> 01:12:52.119
Troen um at the uh formerly known uh

01:12:49.880 --> 01:12:55.560
Devotion School, and I was fortunate to

01:12:52.119 --> 01:12:58.519
I was her intern for a full year.

01:12:55.560 --> 01:13:00.400
I interned in Vivian's class, and I felt
lucky.

01:12:58.520 --> 01:13:04.759
Everyone was smart and cared about
teaching.

01:13:02.720 --> 01:13:09.600
They wanted to work together and learn
about kids.

01:13:07.880 --> 01:13:13.880
They spent time at morning meeting to
learn about kids.

01:13:10.960 --> 01:13:16.760
I thought this was perfect for me.

01:13:13.880 --> 01:13:18.880
Then, Carol Schraft hired me.

01:13:16.760 --> 01:13:23.400
She knew I was a student in that class.

01:13:21.520 --> 01:13:26.839
She knew that teacher was not very good.

01:13:25.119 --> 01:13:30.960
She said, "If you want to teach after that
class, you are hired."

01:13:28.479 --> 01:13:31.839
So, I got the job.

01:13:30.960 --> 01:13:36.439
Um

01:13:31.840 --> 01:13:38.880
Anyway, I loved being an intern for a
whole year.

01:13:36.439 --> 01:13:43.319
I got hired because I knew Brookline well.

01:13:40.920 --> 01:13:47.719
I was part of the learning teaching
collaborative.

01:13:46.640 --> 01:13:53.159
Betsy Fitzpatrick gave us vouchers.

01:13:50.520 --> 01:13:56.479
We didn't pay for them, but we handed them
out.

01:13:54.439 --> 01:13:59.639
We could take courses and do interesting
things.

01:13:57.720 --> 01:14:02.960
So, what kept me in Brookline was
everything you all said.

01:13:59.640 --> 01:14:05.680
My husband, who is over there, didn’t go
to Brookline schools.

01:14:02.960 --> 01:14:09.360
But our kids went to Brookline schools.

01:14:07.880 --> 01:14:14.000
We love it here.

01:14:10.840 --> 01:14:17.119
I live on Westbourne Terrace now.

01:14:15.840 --> 01:14:21.559
I know it sounds a little sad, but it’s
not really sad.

01:14:19.039 --> 01:14:23.840
I am definitely a local.

01:14:21.560 --> 01:14:26.000
I am bringing this up because I want to
share what I want for Brookline.

01:14:23.840 --> 01:14:28.760
Um, I agree with what Liz said.

01:14:26.000 --> 01:14:32.400
Teaching never gets easier.

01:14:30.760 --> 01:14:35.359
Everyone asked if it gets easier, and I
said no.

01:14:33.399 --> 01:14:38.000
It really doesn’t get easier.

01:14:35.359 --> 01:14:40.599
Now, some things my mom said are becoming
true.

01:14:38.000 --> 01:14:43.359
I want to talk to the School Committee
(the elected board that runs the public schools) about this.

01:14:40.600 --> 01:14:45.640
More and more, the curriculum feels like a
conveyor belt.

01:14:43.359 --> 01:14:48.439
This is just my opinion as a fifth grade
teacher.

01:14:45.640 --> 01:14:51.280
I know it's not true for everyone.

01:14:48.439 --> 01:14:53.879
There’s not enough time to know the kids
well.

01:14:51.279 --> 01:14:55.599
There isn’t enough time for morning
meeting.

01:14:53.880 --> 01:14:59.560
I do morning meetings every day.

01:14:56.920 --> 01:15:03.880
everybody, I know. But, there's not enough
time to get to know

01:15:01.960 --> 01:15:08.440
the kids. There's There's not enough time
for morning meeting. I do it every

01:15:05.840 --> 01:15:11.520
The kids love the single day, but we

01:15:08.439 --> 01:15:13.399
must put aside many other things.

01:15:11.520 --> 01:15:18.399
We need to have more, so I will tell you
what I think. Sorry, but we need to

01:15:15.640 --> 01:15:20.920
