fully finalized.

01:51:15.180 --> 01:51:18.159
[cough] Excuse me. Kindergarten [clears
throat]

01:51:16.199 --> 01:51:19.399
is an important change for child
development.

01:51:18.159 --> 01:51:22.839
For five-year-olds coming from small
preschools, entering FR, which is the

01:51:21.159 --> 01:51:27.239
largest elementary school in Brookline, is
a big adjustment. Class size

01:51:25.079 --> 01:51:30.479
matters a lot at this age. Larger classes
mean less personal attention

01:51:28.840 --> 01:51:33.359
during a key time for growth. Fewer adults
watching the children who may be quietly

01:51:31.760 --> 01:51:37.039
struggling, and less help as they learn
how to get around a big public school.

01:51:35.760 --> 01:51:41.319
The district's current reason is that
overall numbers are low, making

01:51:39.079 --> 01:51:44.559
FR average 19.5 students per class. But
looking at this data through an

01:51:43.000 --> 01:51:48.200
equity lens tells a different story. If
you compare English Language Learner (ELL) and Individualized Education Program (IEP) data

01:51:46.640 --> 01:51:51.880
across the district, FR has the highest
numbers by far. We have more

01:51:49.960 --> 01:51:55.400
students with complex needs, but now fewer
teachers to support them.

01:51:54.039 --> 01:51:59.920
Furthermore, framing the removal of the
kindergarten section as a budgetary balance to fund

01:51:57.600 --> 01:52:03.840
a necessary fifth-grade section doesn't
make sense. The needs of a fifth

01:52:02.399 --> 01:52:07.000
grader and a kindergartner are completely
different. Our youngest learners

01:52:05.640 --> 01:52:10.399
should not have to give up their important
first year. If the district must

01:52:09.199 --> 01:52:15.519
cut a section to balance the budget, it
doesn't make sense under an

01:52:13.359 --> 01:52:19.000
equity lens to target FR. Within
Brookline, FR does not have the

01:52:17.000 --> 01:52:22.159
smallest kindergarten classes. It's unfair
to take a section from a school that already has

01:52:20.479 --> 01:52:26.800
higher enrollment and crowd our students,
while

01:52:24.359 --> 01:52:30.320
keeping schools with much lower enrollment
unchanged.

01:52:28.640 --> 01:52:33.840
Finally, relying only on June 1st numbers
is too early. We know enrollment

01:52:31.880 --> 01:52:35.720
changes over the summer.

01:52:33.840 --> 01:52:38.720
In fact, from just talking to my
community, I know of five families with

01:52:37.439 --> 01:52:42.079
kindergartners who are moving to the
neighborhood. They fully

01:52:40.279 --> 01:52:45.119
plan to attend FR this fall, but due to
some moving issues, they have not

01:52:43.359 --> 01:52:46.759
yet been able to officially register.

01:52:45.119 --> 01:52:49.480
Once a section is cut, it is very hard to
reverse. Many of us in the

01:52:48.399 --> 01:52:52.439
community supported the override (a vote
to raise property taxes above the state limit) because we believed it would

01:52:50.600 --> 01:52:55.759
help maintain the quality of Brookline
education. Crowding our

01:52:54.159 --> 01:52:59.000
incoming kindergarten classes is not the
experience we voted to

01:52:57.079 --> 01:53:02.520
preserve. I urge you to keep the fifth FR
kindergarten section open until fall

01:53:00.840 --> 01:53:05.040
enrollment is clear, and to communicate
clearly with our incoming

01:53:03.439 --> 01:53:07.960
families. Thank you for your time, hard
work, and all your help.

01:53:06.039 --> 01:53:10.480
