03:11:21.639 --> 03:11:24.000
Alexandria.

03:11:23.399 --> 03:11:27.280
Thank you. Appreciate your work.

03:11:25.040 --> 03:11:29.542
THANK YOU. [applause]

03:11:30.000 --> 03:11:35.920
OKAY. SOLAR PANEL installation in school

03:11:33.639 --> 03:11:40.600
buildings presentation, Alexandria
Vecchio, and a possible vote to approve

03:11:38.239 --> 03:11:42.119
those solar panels. Alexandria.

03:11:40.600 --> 03:11:44.880
She's on Zoom right now.

03:11:42.120 --> 03:11:47.079
She's on Zoom. Okay, great.

03:11:44.879 --> 03:11:50.319
Hi, good evening everyone. I am Alexandra
Vecchio. I am the Director of Sustainability and

03:11:48.879 --> 03:11:53.479
Asset Resources for the Town of Brookline.
Thank you for your time

03:11:52.040 --> 03:11:55.480
this evening.

03:11:53.479 --> 03:11:59.600
Um I'm just going to pull up my slideshow
now. Give me 1 second.

03:12:11.760 --> 03:12:17.040
Uh okay, great. Uh can everyone see my
slide that says strategic solar

03:12:16.200 --> 03:12:20.760
initiative? Yes. Yes, we can.

03:12:18.280 --> 03:12:24.120
Okay, wonderful. Thank you. Um as I said,
I'm Alexandra. I am the Director of

03:12:22.280 --> 03:12:27.800
Sustainability and Asset Resources for the
town. Um our Deputy Director Shelley

03:12:26.479 --> 03:12:30.639
Dean couldn't be here this evening. She
has been working a lot on

03:12:29.280 --> 03:12:35.519
this and I think she has talked to some of
you before this

03:12:32.719 --> 03:12:39.520
meeting. Um I appreciate everyone’s time
leading up to this meeting on

03:12:38.079 --> 03:12:42.680
this topic. So this evening, um I want to
focus

03:12:41.200 --> 03:12:45.399
specifically on the school projects
because that is what is most interesting

03:12:44.159 --> 03:12:48.600
to you. First, I will give a little
background and context

03:12:46.959 --> 03:12:52.200
because I think that is important to
understand

03:12:50.000 --> 03:12:56.720
what this is about and a bit of the
context around

03:12:53.879 --> 03:12:59.199
what we are doing here.

03:12:56.719 --> 03:13:03.440
In Brookline, we have many municipal solar
projects

03:13:01.799 --> 03:13:08.120
that are currently in operation and under
construction. Right now we have two

03:13:05.399 --> 03:13:11.039
town-owned systems that are quite small

03:13:08.120 --> 03:13:14.960
and a bit older on the library and the
health building. Then we

03:13:13.079 --> 03:13:19.559
have one town-owned system that is under
construction, close to completion at

03:13:17.440 --> 03:13:22.480
the Driscoll School. I am very excited

03:13:19.559 --> 03:13:27.279
about that. I was here with all of you

03:13:22.479 --> 03:13:30.680
last year, or maybe it was 2024. But

03:13:27.280 --> 03:13:34.120
on the Driscoll solar project. We also
have five different solar systems that

03:13:32.680 --> 03:13:38.320
we developed as power purchase agreements.
This means that

03:13:35.879 --> 03:13:41.879
we have rented our rooftop to a solar
developer. This way, we get a

03:13:40.120 --> 03:13:45.479
reduction on our energy bills, but we
don't get all the savings from

03:13:44.040 --> 03:13:50.119
that system. So, right now we have some

03:13:48.040 --> 03:13:54.640
proposed projects that are coming up. One
is at Pierce School and then four other

03:13:52.559 --> 03:13:58.840
sites in town for near-term construction
that are town-owned. We

03:13:57.399 --> 03:14:02.799
are also looking at some medium and long-
term projects and expect town

03:14:01.239 --> 03:14:05.799
ownership for those, but we will need to

03:14:02.799 --> 03:14:09.559
check the finances as we move forward.

03:14:05.799 --> 03:14:11.519
This is all coming from a solar financial
working group that

03:14:09.559 --> 03:14:15.280
was formed over the past year. It included

03:14:13.280 --> 03:14:19.159
members of the Select Board (the town's
elected executive board), the Zero Mission Advisory Board, and the Expenditures

03:14:17.440 --> 03:14:23.479
and Revenues Study Committee, Commissioner
of Public Works, and me.

03:14:21.079 --> 03:14:27.520
Commissioner Shute, and I were looking for
ways to grow solar power in

03:14:25.079 --> 03:14:30.680
town and help save on energy costs.

03:14:27.520 --> 03:14:33.479
This will help us use energy independently
and lower

03:14:30.680 --> 03:14:36.920
electricity bills for everyone in town and
at schools.

03:14:35.239 --> 03:14:40.319
Because of a federal tax credit that is
available but will expire

03:14:36.920 --> 03:14:43.159
soon, we were looking at how to use those
savings quickly and also create

03:14:40.319 --> 03:14:46.239
a long-term money plan.

03:14:43.159 --> 03:14:48.399
We need to work with our building projects
while doing this.

03:14:46.239 --> 03:14:51.079
We will not put solar panels on roofs that
will be fixed or renovated

03:14:48.399 --> 03:14:54.479
in the next 5 years. That would not be
smart.

03:14:51.079 --> 03:14:56.159
Solar panels last over 20 years.

03:14:54.479 --> 03:14:59.879
They often last about 25 years.

03:14:58.079 --> 03:15:03.920
We want to avoid installing something we
will have to remove later.

03:15:01.360 --> 03:15:06.880
We must think about this in relation to
our building upgrades.

03:15:03.920 --> 03:15:10.799
The solar financial working group
suggested that

03:15:09.319 --> 03:15:15.879
the first step is to use the federal
investment tax credit.

03:15:13.159 --> 03:15:19.119
You will hear me call it the ITC tonight.

03:15:15.879 --> 03:15:22.200
This tax credit is running out, and we
want to use it

03:15:20.600 --> 03:15:26.440
for the Driscoll project.

03:15:24.360 --> 03:15:30.600
We are working to use it in the next few
weeks.

03:15:29.079 --> 03:15:33.920
For a project to get this credit,

03:15:30.600 --> 03:15:36.800
you can receive up to 40% or usually
around 30% of costs back.

03:15:33.920 --> 03:15:38.559
You must start construction before July
4th of

03:15:36.799 --> 03:15:42.439
this year, which is just a few weeks away.

03:15:41.040 --> 03:15:46.480
Then, you have four years to finish it.

03:15:44.479 --> 03:15:48.279
You can also start working on it in 2026
or 2027 and complete it by

03:15:46.479 --> 03:15:52.439
December 31st, 2027. That is a short time.

03:15:48.280 --> 03:15:54.920
Driscoll project. And and now

03:15:52.440 --> 03:15:57.600
we are trying to capture here in the

03:15:54.920 --> 03:16:01.079
next few weeks actually. So for a project
to qualify

03:15:59.879 --> 03:16:04.920
receive

03:16:01.079 --> 03:16:06.920
up to 40% but typically around 30% of a

03:16:04.920 --> 03:16:09.879
return on the project. You have to

03:16:06.920 --> 03:16:12.479
commence construction before July 4th of

03:16:09.879 --> 03:16:16.119
this year. So a few weeks from now and
then you have four years to place that

03:16:14.319 --> 03:16:19.119
into service

03:16:16.120 --> 03:16:23.440
or you can place it into service anytime

03:16:19.120 --> 03:16:25.440
in 26 or 27 and start construction

03:16:23.440 --> 03:16:29.760
within there and then complete it by the
December 31st 2027. That's a short time

03:16:27.959 --> 03:16:33.079
When we say "frame especially when placed
into service," we mean it needs to connect with the utility Eversource.

03:16:31.079 --> 03:16:37.479
Everyone is trying to meet this deadline.

03:16:35.040 --> 03:16:39.880
They want to get 30 to 40% back on their
projects.

03:16:37.479 --> 03:16:42.359
We want to give ourselves more time to
start building by July 4th.

03:16:39.879 --> 03:16:45.759
Starting construction does not mean we
need solar panels on the roofs yet.

03:16:42.360 --> 03:16:49.120
It means we need to pay at least 5% of the
project cost.

03:16:47.520 --> 03:16:53.560
We also need a signed agreement to buy the
solar panels by that date.

03:16:51.159 --> 03:16:55.280
We call this a two-track approach.

03:16:53.559 --> 03:17:00.040
Track one is about getting the Investment
Tax Credit by July 4th.

03:16:58.280 --> 03:17:02.200
Track two is looking at longer-term sites.

03:17:00.040 --> 03:17:05.440
We are asking for qualifications from
solar vendors.

03:17:02.200 --> 03:17:09.480
Responses to our request are due at the
end of August.

03:17:05.440 --> 03:17:12.040
We want to find a vendor to look at our
remaining properties.

03:17:09.479 --> 03:17:13.279
They will check site feasibility and
financial options.

03:17:12.040 --> 03:17:17.240
Tonight, I will focus on track one and the
school properties.

03:17:17.920 --> 03:17:24.000
I know those are of most interest.

03:17:20.920 --> 03:17:27.280
This is part of a bigger plan we are
working on.

03:17:24.000 --> 03:17:30.399
The solar projects we are exploring
include Pierce School.

03:17:27.280 --> 03:17:32.600
They are listed in the top row.

03:17:30.399 --> 03:17:35.119
We are also looking at Fire Station 1, the
Main Library, Heath School, and Brookline High School.

03:17:32.600 --> 03:17:39.440
We call it Phase 2.

03:17:37.879 --> 03:17:43.440
Brookline High School already has some
solar panels.

03:17:41.000 --> 03:17:47.800
We will add more panels to the building.

03:17:45.879 --> 03:17:50.920
The current ones are not owned by the
town; they are leased.

03:17:49.159 --> 03:17:55.799
For the Pierce School project, the early
construction cost is $1.13 million.

03:17:53.760 --> 03:17:59.359
This money will come from the Pierce.

03:17:57.040 --> 03:18:02.560
this is a piece of a much larger puzzle
that we're working on.

03:18:02.639 --> 03:18:08.520
So, the uh solar opportunities that we're
looking at right now, one at

03:18:06.600 --> 03:18:12.319
Pierce School, um which you'll see in the
top row there, and then we're

03:18:10.239 --> 03:18:15.920
looking at Fire Station 1, the Main
Library, um

03:18:14.040 --> 03:18:17.240
Heath School, and Brookline High School.

03:18:15.920 --> 03:18:18.280
We're referring to it as Phase 2.

03:18:17.239 --> 03:18:22.120
Brookline High School actually already
does have solar panels on part of the

03:18:20.040 --> 03:18:25.520
building, so we would be adding on to
that. Um the ones that are there

03:18:23.719 --> 03:18:30.399
currently are not owned by the town, those
are uh part of a leasing

03:18:27.079 --> 03:18:33.079
structure. Um and so, for the purposes

03:18:30.399 --> 03:18:34.879
of the Pierce School project, uh the

03:18:33.079 --> 03:18:38.559
preliminary construction costs we're

03:18:34.879 --> 03:18:40.920
looking at is $1.13 million.

03:18:38.559 --> 03:18:43.439
Um that would be coming from the Pierce

03:18:40.920 --> 03:18:47.720
The project budget has been reviewed and
voted on by the Building Commission.

03:18:46.559 --> 03:18:52.119
The other projects are important too.

03:18:50.360 --> 03:18:56.360
Especially the Heath School and Brookline
High School projects.

03:18:55.000 --> 03:19:01.319
The money for these projects will come
from a Capital Improvement Plan (CIP) item.

03:18:58.440 --> 03:19:04.560
This item was voted on through Town
Meeting (the town's legislature — elected members who vote on budgets and laws) just last month.

03:19:01.319 --> 03:19:07.520
The amount is $3.2 million.

03:19:04.559 --> 03:19:10.639
This money will be used for these projects
and future solar projects too.

03:19:07.520 --> 03:19:13.280
None of this money will come from the
schools' budget.

03:19:10.639 --> 03:19:15.799
I will go through each project now.

03:19:13.280 --> 03:19:19.560
The estimated cost for Brookline High
School is $688,000.

03:19:15.799 --> 03:19:21.759
The cost for the second phase of solar at
Brookline High School is $878,000.

03:19:19.559 --> 03:19:25.359
For context, Pierce School has a 325
kilowatt (kW) system.

03:19:21.760 --> 03:19:27.319
Heath School has a 200 kW system.

03:19:25.360 --> 03:19:30.000
Brookline High School has a 261 kW system.

03:19:27.319 --> 03:19:33.600
These are all large systems.

03:19:30.000 --> 03:19:36.040
Driscoll School has about a 200 kW system.

03:19:33.600 --> 03:19:40.560
This is the most recent system we
installed.

03:19:39.079 --> 03:19:43.879
For Pierce, we are holding some extra
money just in case.

03:19:42.280 --> 03:19:47.960
This is to meet the July 4th deadline for
getting the Investment Tax Credit (ITC).

03:19:43.879 --> 03:19:50.159
We are looking at a preliminary cost of
$1.13 million.

03:19:47.959 --> 03:19:54.280
This includes money for roofing over the
mechanical systems for solar installation.

03:19:52.239 --> 03:19:59.120
This will help us use the extra space on
the roof.

03:19:56.280 --> 03:20:02.440
There is also a $50,000 contingency for
the racking system to attach solar panels to the roof.

03:19:59.120 --> 03:20:03.880
There is an overall construction
contingency too.

03:20:02.440 --> 03:20:07.159
This project may end up costing less than
$1.1 million.

03:20:03.879 --> 03:20:09.639
But we will make sure we set aside enough
money.

03:20:07.159 --> 03:20:12.039
comply with what is necessary for that

03:20:09.639 --> 03:20:15.959
July 4th deadline to be able to capture

03:20:12.040 --> 03:20:18.960
the ITC. And so, we are looking at

03:20:15.959 --> 03:20:22.879
a preliminary cost of 1.13 million. That
includes an allocation

03:20:21.280 --> 03:20:25.920
of

03:20:22.879 --> 03:20:28.719
some contingency for both roofing over

03:20:25.920 --> 03:20:30.559
the mechanical systems where we would

03:20:28.719 --> 03:20:35.680
like to install solar there as well to
take advantage of the additional space

03:20:33.000 --> 03:20:38.280
up there. And then a contingency of

03:20:35.680 --> 03:20:41.920
50,000 for the racking system that we use
to connect the solar to the roof.

03:20:40.600 --> 03:20:45.920
And then an overall construction
contingency. So, at the end, this

03:20:43.840 --> 03:20:49.760
project may actually end up being less
than 1.1

03:20:47.559 --> 03:20:52.519
million, but we are

03:20:49.760 --> 03:20:55.440
going to make sure we put enough of a

03:20:52.520 --> 03:20:57.920
down payment to meet that Investment Tax
Credit requirement.

03:20:55.440 --> 03:21:00.520
In this case, the payback time for Pierce
would be less than a year.

03:20:57.920 --> 03:21:04.840
This is after you consider state
incentives we can receive for this project.

03:21:02.639 --> 03:21:06.479
We also consider savings from the
Investment Tax Credit.

03:21:04.840 --> 03:21:11.319
We expect positive results from our
electric bills.

03:21:06.479 --> 03:21:16.799
We are looking at a system that shows a
net gain in our first year,

03:21:11.319 --> 03:21:17.399
which is very impressive.

03:21:16.799 --> 03:21:23.119
For Hayes School, a 200 kilowatt system
has a preliminary cost of $688,000.

03:21:20.280 --> 03:21:26.600
We expect the payback time to be just over
6 years.

03:21:25.520 --> 03:21:29.319
Right now, we are using a 5% safety margin
because we haven’t done a final check.

03:21:26.600 --> 03:21:32.800
If any of these systems are smaller or
cost less, the actual contracts and bills will show that.

03:21:29.319 --> 03:21:34.760
For Hayes School, the cash flow
predictions show that once we consider

03:21:32.799 --> 03:21:38.520
the state incentive money and after the
Investment Tax Credit return of $481,000,

03:21:36.680 --> 03:21:42.000
